re generally listed under the [[Bengali language]]. Some films before 1971 were mixed [[Urdu]] and Bengali language.\n{{Bangladeshi film list}}\n\n== 1928\u20131947 ==\nThis is a list of notable Bengali-language films produced in former British [[Bengal Presidency]] during 1928 to 1947.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:19%;\" |Title\n! style=\"width:15%;\" |Director\n! style=\"width:25%;\" |Cast\n! Genre\n! Release date\n! Notes\n! Ref(s)\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1928 in film|1928]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''Sukumari'' || Ambuj Gupta || Nasrullah, Abdus Sobhan (a male playing the female role) || || || A silent short film and the first film venture of this region. The screening was private. ||\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1931 in film|1931]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''The Last Kiss'' || Ambuj Gupta || Khwaja Ajmal, Lolita, Charu Bala || || || The first full-length silent film ||\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1934 in film|1934]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''Dhruba'' || || Poet [[Kazi Nazrul Islam]] || || || A Calcutta-based short non-silent film ||\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1946 in film|1946]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''Dukhe Jader Jibon Gora'' || [[Obaidul Huq]] || [[Jahar Ganguly]], [[Renuka Roy]], [[Fateh Lohani]] || || || A Calcutta-based full-length feature film, first film made by a Bengali Muslim ||\n|}\n\n== 1948\u20131969 ==\nThis is a list of notable films produced in [[East Pakistan]] (now [[Bangladesh]]) both in Bengali and [[Urdu]] languages. A total of 214 films were made since 1948\u20131971 in Dhaka. Among them 158 films were Bengali and 57 Urdu.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:19%;\" |Title\n! style=\"width:15%;\" |Director\n! style=\"width:25%;\" |Cast\n! Genre\n! Release date\n! Notes\n! Ref(s)\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1954 in film|1954]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''Salamat''\n| Nazir Ahmed\n|\n|\n|\n| A short documentary\n|<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://issuu.com/documentarytoday/docs/documentary_today_02 |title=Cinema with a cause |last=Kabir |first=Alamgir |date=November 2007 |journal=Documentary Today |doi= |pmid= |access-date=22 January 2015 |volume=1 |issue=2 |orig-year=November 2007 |last2=Mokammel |first2=Tanvir |pages=39\u201342}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1956 in film|1956]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''[[Mukh-o-Mukhush]]'' || Abdul Jabbar Khan || Abdul Jabbar Khan, Ahmed, Purnima Sen, Nazma (Peary), Zaharat Ara, Ali Mansur || [[Drama]] || || The first full-length non-silent \"[[talkie]]\" film, and considered as the first properly developed feature film of the region. It took 3 years to complete the film, while none of the cast had any prior experience in films. ||\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1959 in film|1959]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''[[Akash Aar Mati]]'' || [[Fateh Lohani]] || Amin, [[Prabir Kumar]], [[Sumita Devi]] || || || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Ei Desh Tomar Amar]]'' || [[Ehtesham]] || Sumita Devi, Khan Ataur Rahman, Rehman, Madhavi Chatterjee, [[Subhash Dutta]] || || || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Matir Pahar]]'' || [[Mohiuddin]] || Sumita Devi || || || ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Day Shall Dawn]]'' || [[A. J. Kardar]] || [[Khan Ataur Rahman|Khan Ata]], [[Tripti Mitra]] || || || The film won the Best Picture award in 1960 Moscow Film Festival. The story was taken from the popular novel written by [[Manik Bandopadhyay]]. The film was submitted for the [[32nd Academy Awards]] in the Best Foreign Language Film category. ||\n|-\n| {{Year header}} | <center>'''[[1960 in film|1960]]'''</center>\n|-\n| ''[[Asiya (film)|Asiya]]'' || Fateh Lohani || Sumita Devi, Kazi Khaliq, Ranen Kushad, Shahid || || || The film won the Presidents Award for the year. The Music director was Abbasuddin Ahmed. [[Shabnam]] played as the child artist in the film. ||\n|-\n| ''Rajdhanir Buke'' || Ehtesham || Rehman, Chitra, Subhash Dutta, Nargis, Shabnam || || || A Musical Hit! [[Robin Ghosh]] and [[Ferdausi Rahman]] (Begum) collaborated in music direction. |