National League]] for [[FC Yenisey Krasnoyarsk]] on 27 October 2013 in a game against [[FC Arsenal Tula]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Russian Football Union]] |url=http://rfspro.ru/cgi-bin/player/script2.cgi?par1=117878 |title=Career Summary |date=28 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201192002/http://rfspro.ru/cgi-bin/player/script2.cgi?par1=117878 |archivedate=1 February 2014 }}</ref> In March 2017, he joined [[Moldova]]n club [[FC Academia Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Academia Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]; he made his debut against [[FC Saxan|Saxan]] on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web | title = \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \"\u0434\u0437\u044e\u0434\u043e\u0438\u0441\u0442\" \u0434\u0435\u0431\u044e\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0437\u0430 \"\u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044e\" | url = http://moldova.sports.md/football/national_division/news/17-03-2017/135971/moskovskij_dz_udoist_deb_utiroval_za_akademiju/ | publisher = moldova.sports.md | date = 17 March 2017 | language = Russian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/Anton-Sergeevich-Polyutkin-Futbol-02021993/turnir_8842 Career summary by sportbox.ru]\n* {{Soccerway|anton-polyutkin/263400}}\n\n{{FC Tyumen squad}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polyutkin, Anton}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:People from Naberezhnye Chelny]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian footballers]]\n[[Category:Russia youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Yenisey Krasnoyarsk players]]\n[[Category:FC Solyaris Moscow players]]\n[[Category:PFC Montana players]]\n[[Category:FC Academia Chi\u0219in\u0103u players]]\n[[Category:First Professional Football League (Bulgaria) players]]\n[[Category:Moldovan National Division players]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate sportspeople in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate sportspeople in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:FC Sibir Novosibirsk players]]\n[[Category:PFC CSKA Moscow players]]\n[[Category:FC Tyumen players]]\n\n{{Russia-footy-defender-1993-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update sportbox.ru link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anton_Polyutkin"}
{"title_page": "Overboard (1987 film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name          = Overboard\n| image         = Overboard film.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Theatrical release poster\n| director      = [[Garry Marshall]]\n| producer      = {{Plainlist|\n* Nick Abdo\n* [[Roddy McDowall]]\n* Alexandra Rose\n* [[Anthea Sylbert]]\n}}\n| writer        = [[Leslie Dixon]]\n| starring      = {{plainlist|\n* [[Goldie Hawn]]\n* [[Kurt Russell]]\n* [[Edward Herrmann]]\n* [[Katherine Helmond]]\n* Roddy McDowall\n}}\n| music          = [[Alan Silvestri]]\n| cinematography = [[John A. Alonzo]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Sonny Baskin\n* Dov Hoenig\n}}\n| studio = Star Partners Ltd.\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1987|12|18}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 112:05--><ref>{{cite web | title=''OVERBOARD'' (PG) | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/overboard-1970-3 | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=January 8, 1988 | accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $22 million<ref name=VF>{{cite web | title=30 Years Later: Why Overboard Needed Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell| url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/12/overboard-goldie-hawn-kurt-russell-30th-anniversary| work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] | date=December 25, 2017| accessdate=May 2, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $26.7 million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=overboard.htm|title=Overboard (1987)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Overboard''''' is a 1987 American [[romantic comedy|romantic comedy film]] directed by [[Garry Marshall]], written by [[Leslie Dixon]], starring [[Goldie Hawn]] and [[Kurt Russell]],<ref>{{cite news|title= Revenge of the epic movie flops|publisher= [[The Independent|Independent]]|date=2010-04-12|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/revenge-of-the-epic-movie-flops-1942105.html|accessdate=2010-07-04|location=London}}</ref> and produced by [[Roddy McDowall]], who also co-stars. The film's soundtrack was composed by [[Alan Silvestri]]. \nAlthough it opened to mixed reviews and was a box office disappointment, ''Overboard'' has grown into a [[cult film|cult]] [[cult following|status]] over the years and has been remade twice. In 1992, it was adapted in the [[Indian cinema|Indian film]] [[Ek Ladka Ek Ladki]], in 2006, it was adapted into the South Korean television series ''[[Couple or Trouble]]'' and in 2018 it was [[Overboard (2018 film)|remade]] with [[Anna Faris]] and [[Eugenio Derbez]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be 400-700 words. -->\nHeiress Joanna Stayton is accustomed to a wealthy life with her husband, Grant Stayton III. While waiting for their yacht to be repaired in the rural hamlet of Elk Cove, Oregon, she hires local carpenter Dean Proffitt to remodel her closet. He puts up with her rude and condescending attitude, and produces quality work, which is dismissed by her because he used [[oak]] instead of [[cedar wood|cedar]], despite her not having specifically requested this at the start.\n\nHe agrees to redo the closet, if he is paid for the work he has already done. She refuses to pay and they have an argument, during which he notes that she is inventing things to complain about because her life is so pampered and boring. This is overheard by the yacht's crew on the [[intercom]], who applaud him for telling her off. Their argument concludes with her pushing him off the yacht and throwing his tools into the ocean.\n\nThat night, as the yacht sails away, Joanna goes on deck to retrieve her wedding ring; she suddenly loses her balance and falls overboard. The next day, a story is aired on the local TV news about her having been picked out of the water by a [[garbage scow]]. She is suffering from [[amnesia]], and is taken to the local hospital, where no one can determine her identity. Once Grant discovers that she has fallen overboard, he sails back to retrieve her. After seeing her mental state and her lashing out at hospital employees, he denies knowing her, and returns to the yacht to embark on a spree of parties with younger women.\n\nAfter seeing her story on the news, Dean, who is a widower living in squalor with four sons, seeks revenge by encouraging Joanna to [[debt bondage|work off her unpaid bill]]. Despite pleas from his best friend, Billy, not to follow through on his impulse, he goes to the hospital and tells her that she is Annie, his wife of thirteen years and the mother of his four sons. She reluctantly goes home with him and is appalled by his residence.\n\nJoanna initially has difficulty dealing with Dean's sons and the heavy load of chores, but she soon adapts. As she masters her responsibilities, she learns about the boys' school and family issues, and that Dean is secretly working two jobs to pay bills. She falls in love with him and develops motherly love toward his sons, and starts streamlining the money problems with more efficient budgeting. Joanna also convinces Dean to be a father to his sons rather than simply be their friend, as his sons are doing poorly in school and struggle with literacy, yet he simply brushes these issues aside rather than fix them.\n\nJoanna makes Dean's dream come true by helping him design a [[miniature golf]] course. Although he has also fallen in love with her, he does not tell her the truth about her real identity for fear that she will leave. Billy, who created doctored photos of the couple to cement the alibi of their marriage, tells Dean that his family needs Joanna.\n\nJoanna's mother, Edith, learns that Grant abandoned Joanna at the hospital and has been lying to her about her daughter's condition. After Edith threatens Grant (who is in [[Los Angeles]]) that she will hire mercenaries to hunt him down, he reluctantly ends the partying and returns to Elk Cove to retrieve Joanna, whose memory is instantaneously restored upon seeing him. She is shocked and hurt when she realizes that Dean lied and has been using her for months, and returns with Grant to their yacht, which is headed for [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\nJoanna now finds her old lifestyle boring and pretentious. She is particularly offended by how rude and haughtily Grant and Edith treat the boat staff. She apologizes to her butler, Andrew, for her spiteful treatment of him over the years. He then helps Joanna to realize how happy she was with Dean and his sons. Joanna commandeers the yacht and turns back towards Elk Cove. The next morning when Grant finds out that Joanna loves Dean and wants to return back to the life she had before regaining her memory, Grant becomes insane and takes charge of the boat; Joanna reveals she doesn't love him anymore, and Grant reveals that he purposely abandoned her and had numerous affairs with other women in her absence. Dean and the boys arrive on a [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] boat with the intention of rescuing Joanna, but they are soon called away due to a sighting of salmon poachers. Dean grabs a life jacket and dives into the water towards the yacht and Joanna does likewise before letting Andrew know to tell her mother that she'll give her a phone call. Grant, now having a mental breakdown, furiously takes aim at her with a [[bow and arrow]], only to be purposely booted overboard into the water by Andrew, who then gives his two weeks [[Notice period|notice]]. After reuniting, Joanna tells Dean that all of the money and the yacht is actually hers, not Grant's. As the boys eagerly make out their [[Wish list|Christmas lists]], Dean asks Joanna what he could possibly give her that she doesn't already have. Joanna smiles and replies, \"A little girl.\" The film ends with Dean and Joanna kissing as the boat sails off into the sunset.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Goldie Hawn]] as Joanna Stayton/Annie Proffitt\n* [[Kurt Russell]] as Dean Proffitt\n* [[Edward Herrmann]] as Grant Stayton III\n* [[Katherine Helmond]] as Edith Mintz\n* [[Roddy McDowall]] as Andrew\n* [[Michael G. Hagerty]] as Billy Pratt\n* [[Brian Price]] as Travis Proffitt\n* [[Jared Rushton]] as Charlie Proffitt\n* Jamie Wild as Greg Proffitt\n* [[Jeffrey Wiseman]] as Joey Proffitt\n* [[Henry Alan Miller]] as Dr. Norman Korman\n* [[Hector Elizondo]] as Garbage Scow Captain Tenati\n* [[Sven-Ole Thorsen]] as Olaf\n* [[Garry Marshall]] as Drummer\n* [[Ray Combs]] as the cop at the hospital\n* [[Doris Hess]] as Principal Adele Burbridge\n* [[Frank Buxton]] as Wilbur Budd\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\n\n===Box office===\nThe film made $1.9 million in its first weekend, $2.9 million in its second (+34%) and $3.9 million in its third (+54%), totaling $26.7 million by the end of its run.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n===Critical reception===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 42% based on 31 reviews, with an average rating of 5.05/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell's comedic chops elevate waterlogged material, but not even their buoyant chemistry can keep ''Overboard'''s creepy concept afloat\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/overboard/|title=Overboard|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 53 out of 100, based on 13 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/overboard|title=Overboard Reviews |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=May 2, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale.\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised Hawn's performance, but called the film \"an uninspiring, unsophisticated attempt at an updated screwball comedy that is brought down by plodding script and a handful of too broadly drawn characters.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Overboard|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1986-12-31|url=https://variety.com/1986/film/reviews/overboard-1200427160/|accessdate=2010-12-26}}</ref> Rita Kempley of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called it \"a deeply banal farce\" with \"one-dimensional characters, a good long look at her buttocks and lots of pathetic sex jokes.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Overboard|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=1987-12-16|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/overboardpg13kempley_a0ca32.htm|accessdate=2010-12-26}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] liked it; while calling it predictable, he wrote: \"the things that make it special, however, are the genuine charm, wit and warm energy generated by the entire cast and director Garry Marshall.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Overboard|publisher= [[Chicago Sun Times]]|url= http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19871216/REVIEWS/712160301|accessdate=2010-12-26}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''' review of it read: \"The film tries to mix the two 1930s movie comedy strains: screwball romance and populist fable. But there's something nerveless and thin about it. Hawn and Russell are good, but their scenes together have a calculated spontaneity\u2014overcute, obvious.\"<ref>{{cite news|title= MOVIE REVIEW : Hawn Keeps 'Overboard' From Sinking|publisher=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1987-12-18|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1987-12-18/entertainment/ca-19770_1|accessdate=2010-12-25|first=Michael|last=Wilmington}}</ref>\n\nThe film has gone on to be considered a [[cult film|cult]] [[cult following|classic]].<ref name=VF/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/05/goldie-hawn-and-kurt-russell-rewatched-overboard-together.html|title=Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell Watched Overboard and Fell in Love Again|first=Jackson|last=McHenry|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-4287636/Anna-Faris-Derbez-Goldie-Hawn-Kurt-Russell-Overboard.html|title=Anna Faris and Eugenio Derbez to recreate Goldie Hawn's Overboard|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Remakes==\n{{main|Overboard (2018 film)|Ek Ladka Ek Ladki}}\n\nA [[remake|reimagined]] [[Overboard (2018 film)|film of the same name]], starring [[Anna Faris]] and [[Eugenio Derbez]], was released on May 4, 2018. The main roles are reversed from the 1987 original. Derbez portrays a wealthy man who falls off of his yacht and is found by Faris' character, a single mother who convinces him that he is her husband.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gonzales|first=Umberto |title='Overboard' Remake: Anna Faris and Eugenio Derbez Set to Star |url=http://www.thewrap.com/overboard-remake-anna-faris-eugenio-derbez/ |website=[[The Wrap]] |accessdate=2017-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McNary |first=Dave |title=Anna Faris-Eugenio Derbez Comedy 'Overboard' Lands April Release |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/anna-faris-eugenio-derbez-overboard-release-date-1202501780/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=20 July 2017 |accessdate=2017-07-29}}</ref>\n\nA loose adaptation of ''Overboard'' is the 1992 [[Bollywood|Hindi]] film ''[[Ek Ladka Ek Ladki]]'', directed by Vijay Sadanah and starring [[Salman Khan]] and [[Neelam Kothari]]. \n\nThe 1997 [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Mayaponman]]'' is another loose adaptation.\n\nThe 2006 [[Korean drama|South Korean television show]] ''[[Couple or Trouble]]'', starring [[Han Ye-seul]] and [[Oh Ji-ho]] and directed by Kim Sang Ho, is also a loose adaptation of the film.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0093693}}\n* {{amg movie|36936}}\n* {{tcmdb title|17699}}\n* {{AFI film|57777}}\n* {{Mojo title|overboard}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|overboard}}\n\n{{Garry Marshall}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Overboard}}\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1980s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Silvestri]]\n[[Category:Films about amnesia]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Garry Marshall]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name          = Overboard\n| image         = Overboard film.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Theatrical release poster\n| director      = [[Garry Marshall]]\n| producer      = {{Plainlist|\n* Nick Abdo\n* [[Roddy McDowall]]\n* Alexandra Rose\n* [[Anthea Sylbert]]\n}}\n| writer        = [[Leslie Dixon]]\n| starring      = {{plainlist|\n* [[Goldie Hawn]]\n* [[Kurt Russell]]\n* [[Edward Herrmann]]\n* [[Katherine Helmond]]\n* Roddy McDowall\n}}\n| music          = [[Alan Silvestri]]\n| cinematography = [[John A. Alonzo]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Sonny Baskin\n* Dov Hoenig\n}}\n| studio = Star Partners Ltd.\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1987|12|18}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 112:05--><ref>{{cite web | title=''OVERBOARD'' (PG) | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/overboard-1970-3 | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=January 8, 1988 | accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $22 million<ref name=VF>{{cite web | title=30 Years Later: Why Overboard Needed Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell| url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/12/overboard-goldie-hawn-kurt-russell-30th-anniversary| work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] | date=December 25, 2017| accessdate=May 2, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $26.7 million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=overboard.htm|title=Overboard (1987)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Overboard''''' is a 1987 American [[romantic comedy|romantic comedy film]] directed by [[Garry Marshall]], written by [[Leslie Dixon]], starring [[Goldie Hawn]] and [[Kurt Russell]],<ref>{{cite news|title= Revenge of the epic movie flops|publisher= [[The Independent|Independent]]|date=2010-04-12|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/revenge-of-the-epic-movie-flops-1942105.html|accessdate=2010-07-04|location=London}}</ref> and produced by [[Roddy McDowall]], who also co-stars. The film's soundtrack was composed by [[Alan Silvestri]]. \nAlthough it opened to mixed reviews and was a box office disappointment, ''Overboard'' has grown into a [[cult film|cult]] [[cult following|status]] over the years and has been remade twice. In 1992, it was adapted in the [[Indian cinema|Indian film]] [[Ek Ladka Ek Ladki]], in 2006, it was adapted into the South Korean television series ''[[Couple or Trouble]]'' and in 2018 it was [[Overboard (2018 film)|remade]] with [[Anna Faris]] and [[Eugenio Derbez]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be 400-700 words. -->\nHeiress Joanna Stayton is accustomed to a wealthy life with her husband, Grant Stayton III. While waiting for their yacht to be repaired in the rural hamlet of Elk Cove, Oregon, she hires local carpenter Dean Proffitt to remodel her closet. He puts up with her rude and condescending attitude, and produces quality work, which is dismissed by her because he used [[oak]] instead of [[cedar wood|cedar]], despite her not having specifically requested this at the start.\n\nHe agrees to redo the closet, if he is paid for the work he has already done. She refuses to pay and they have an argument, during which he notes that she is inventing things to complain about because her life is so pampered and boring. This is overheard by the yacht's crew on the [[intercom]], who applaud him for telling her off. Their argument concludes with her pushing him off the yacht and throwing his tools into the ocean.\n\nThat night, as the yacht sails away, Joanna goes on deck to retrieve her wedding ring; she suddenly loses her balance and falls overboard. The next day, a story is aired on the local TV news about her having been picked out of the water by a [[garbage scow]]. She is suffering from [[amnesia]], and is taken to the local hospital, where no one can determine her identity. Once Grant discovers that she has fallen overboard, he sails back to retrieve her. After seeing her mental state and her lashing out at hospital employees, he denies knowing her, and returns to the yacht to embark on a spree of parties with younger women.\n\nAfter seeing her story on the news, Dean, who is a widower living in squalor with four sons, seeks revenge by encouraging Joanna to [[debt bondage|work off her unpaid bill]]. Despite pleas from his best friend, Billy, not to follow through on his impulse, he goes to the hospital and tells her that she is Annie, his wife of thirteen years and the mother of his four sons. She reluctantly goes home with him and is appalled by his residence.\n\nJoanna initially has difficulty dealing with Dean's sons and the heavy load of chores, but she soon adapts. As she masters her responsibilities, she learns about the boys' school and family issues, and that Dean is secretly working two jobs to pay bills. She falls in love with him and develops motherly love toward his sons, and starts streamlining the money problems with more efficient budgeting. Joanna also convinces Dean to be a father to his sons rather than simply be their friend, as his sons are doing poorly in school and struggle with literacy, yet he simply brushes these issues aside rather than fix them.\n\nJoanna makes Dean's dream come true by helping him design a [[miniature golf]] course. Although he has also fallen in love with her, he does not tell her the truth about her real identity for fear that she will leave. Billy, who created doctored photos of the couple to cement the alibi of their marriage, tells Dean that his family needs Joanna.\n\nJoanna's mother, Edith, learns that Grant abandoned Joanna at the hospital and has been lying to her about her daughter's condition. After Edith threatens Grant (who is in [[Los Angeles]]) that she will hire mercenaries to hunt him down, he reluctantly ends the partying and returns to Elk Cove to retrieve Joanna, whose memory is instantaneously restored upon seeing him. She is shocked and hurt when she realizes that Dean lied and has been using her for months, and returns with Grant to their yacht, which is headed for [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\nJoanna now finds her old lifestyle boring and pretentious. She is particularly offended by how rude and haughtily Grant and Edith treat the boat staff. She apologizes to her butler, Andrew, for her spiteful treatment of him over the years. He then helps Joanna to realize how happy she was with Dean and his sons. Joanna commandeers the yacht and turns back towards Elk Cove. The next morning when Grant finds out that Joanna loves Dean and wants to return back to the life she had before regaining her memory, Grant becomes insane and takes charge of the boat; Joanna reveals she doesn't love him anymore, and Grant reveals that he purposely abandoned her and had numerous affairs with other women in her absence. Dean and the boys arrive on a [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] boat with the intention of rescuing Joanna, but they are soon called away due to a sighting of salmon poachers. Dean grabs a life jacket and dives into the water towards the yacht and Joanna does likewise before letting Andrew know to tell her mother that she'll give her a phone call. Grant, now having a mental breakdown, furiously takes aim at her with a [[bow and arrow]], only to be purposely booted overboard into the water by Andrew, who then gives his two weeks [[Notice period|notice]]. After reuniting, Joanna tells Dean that all of the money and the yacht is actually hers, not Grant's. As the boys eagerly make out their [[Wish list|Christmas lists]], Dean asks Joanna what he could possibly give her that she doesn't already have. Joanna smiles and replies, \"A little girl.\" The film ends with Dean and Joanna kissing as the boat sails off into the sunset.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Goldie Hawn]] as Joanna Stayton/Annie Proffitt\n* [[Kurt Russell]] as Dean Proffitt\n* [[Edward Herrmann]] as Grant Stayton III\n* [[Katherine Helmond]] as Edith Mintz\n* [[Roddy McDowall]] as Andrew\n* [[Michael G. Hagerty]] as Billy Pratt\n* [[Brian Price]] as Travis Proffitt\n* [[Jared Rushton]] as Charlie Proffitt\n* Jamie Wild as Greg Proffitt\n* [[Jeffrey Wiseman]] as Joey Proffitt\n* [[Henry Alan Miller]] as Dr. Norman Korman\n* [[Hector Elizondo]] as Garbage Scow Captain Tenati\n* [[Sven-Ole Thorsen]] as Olaf\n* [[Garry Marshall]] as Drummer\n* [[Ray Combs]] as the cop at the hospital\n* [[Doris Hess]] as Principal Adele Burbridge\n* [[Frank Buxton]] as Wilbur Budd\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\n\n===Box office===\nThe film made $1.9 million in its first weekend, $2.9 million in its second (+34%) and $3.9 million in its third (+54%), totaling $26.7 million by the end of its run.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n===Critical reception===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 42% based on 31 reviews, with an average rating of 5.05/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell's comedic chops elevate waterlogged material, but not even their buoyant chemistry can keep ''Overboard'''s creepy concept afloat\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/overboard/|title=Overboard|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 53 out of 100, based on 13 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/overboard|title=Overboard Reviews |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=May 2, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale.\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised Hawn's performance, but called the film \"an uninspiring, unsophisticated attempt at an updated screwball comedy that is brought down by plodding script and a handful of too broadly drawn characters.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Overboard|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1986-12-31|url=https://variety.com/1986/film/reviews/overboard-1200427160/|accessdate=2010-12-26}}</ref> Rita Kempley of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called it \"a deeply banal farce\" with \"one-dimensional characters, a good long look at her buttocks and lots of pathetic sex jokes.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Overboard|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=1987-12-16|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/overboardpg13kempley_a0ca32.htm|accessdate=2010-12-26}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] liked it; while calling it predictable, he wrote: \"the things that make it special, however, are the genuine charm, wit and warm energy generated by the entire cast and director Garry Marshall.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Overboard|publisher= [[Chicago Sun Times]]|url= http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19871216/REVIEWS/712160301|accessdate=2010-12-26}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''' review of it read: \"The film tries to mix the two 1930s movie comedy strains: screwball romance and populist fable. But there's something nerveless and thin about it. Hawn and Russell are good, but their scenes together have a calculated spontaneity\u2014overcute, obvious.\"<ref>{{cite news|title= MOVIE REVIEW : Hawn Keeps 'Overboard' From Sinking|publisher=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1987-12-18|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1987-12-18/entertainment/ca-19770_1|accessdate=2010-12-25|first=Michael|last=Wilmington}}</ref>\n\nThe film has gone on to be considered a [[cult classic]].<ref name=VF/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/05/goldie-hawn-and-kurt-russell-rewatched-overboard-together.html|title=Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell Watched Overboard and Fell in Love Again|first=Jackson|last=McHenry|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-4287636/Anna-Faris-Derbez-Goldie-Hawn-Kurt-Russell-Overboard.html|title=Anna Faris and Eugenio Derbez to recreate Goldie Hawn's Overboard|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Remakes==\n{{main|Overboard (2018 film)|Ek Ladka Ek Ladki}}\n\nA [[remake|reimagined]] [[Overboard (2018 film)|film of the same name]], starring [[Anna Faris]] and [[Eugenio Derbez]], was released on May 4, 2018. The main roles are reversed from the 1987 original. Derbez portrays a wealthy man who falls off of his yacht and is found by Faris' character, a single mother who convinces him that he is her husband.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gonzales|first=Umberto |title='Overboard' Remake: Anna Faris and Eugenio Derbez Set to Star |url=http://www.thewrap.com/overboard-remake-anna-faris-eugenio-derbez/ |website=[[The Wrap]] |accessdate=2017-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McNary |first=Dave |title=Anna Faris-Eugenio Derbez Comedy 'Overboard' Lands April Release |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/anna-faris-eugenio-derbez-overboard-release-date-1202501780/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=20 July 2017 |accessdate=2017-07-29}}</ref>\n\nA loose adaptation of ''Overboard'' is the 1992 [[Bollywood|Hindi]] film ''[[Ek Ladka Ek Ladki]]'', directed by Vijay Sadanah and starring [[Salman Khan]] and [[Neelam Kothari]]. \n\nThe 1997 [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Mayaponman]]'' is another loose adaptation.\n\nThe 2006 [[Korean drama|South Korean television show]] ''[[Couple or Trouble]]'', starring [[Han Ye-seul]] and [[Oh Ji-ho]] and directed by Kim Sang Ho, is also a loose adaptation of the film.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0093693}}\n* {{amg movie|36936}}\n* {{tcmdb title|17699}}\n* {{AFI film|57777}}\n* {{